# i18n Unified Resolver

Multi-language support uses ONE home-grown resolver — NOT
`next-intl`. The full contract (when to use `tStatic` vs
`tDynamic`, the composition order with `field-label-case`, the
`meta.translations` shape, the `<TranslationsEditor>` panel, the
locale resolution chain, and the explicit "PDFs / emails stay
English" boundary) lives in
[`.cursor/skills/i18n/SKILL.md`](mdc:.cursor/skills/i18n/SKILL.md).

If your task touches **any** of the following, STOP and read the
skill **before** writing code:

- Adding ANY user-facing string in `app/(dashboard)/**` or
  `components/**`
- Adding a new admin-configurable list whose labels appear in the
  dashboard UI (statuses, workflow actions, document types,
  package fields, premium roles, etc.)
- Wiring `tDynamic` into a new consumer of `form_options`
- Adding a new admin editor that exposes a "Label" input
- Editing `lib/i18n/**`, `messages/**`, `proxy.ts`,
  `app/api/me/locale/route.ts`,
  `components/admin/i18n/TranslationsEditor.tsx`, or
  `components/ui/locale-switcher.tsx`
- Adding a new locale to `SUPPORTED_LOCALES`
- Adding a new column / table / drawer that renders labels from
  `form_options.label`
- Debugging "language switcher doesn't update X / X still renders
  in English / X renders raw key / X breaks the column case
  transform / locale didn't persist across sessions"
- Touching `applyLabelCase` / `applyCaseToText` / any `applyCase`
  call site (translation MUST run first; see
  `field-label-case` skill cross-reference)

## The 30-second cheatsheet

| Concern | Pattern | Don't do |
|---|---|---|
| Hardcoded UI string in client JSX | `const t = useT(); t("section.key", "English fallback")` | `<span>Confirm</span>` |
| Hardcoded UI string in server component | `tStatic("section.key", await getLocale(), "English fallback")` | Hardcode the literal |
| Admin-edited label from `form_options` | `tDynamic({ label: row.label, meta: row.meta }, locale)` | `String(row.label ?? "")` |
| Translation + `labelCase` | `applyCase(tDynamic(row, locale), row.meta?.labelCase)` — translate FIRST, case AFTER | `applyCase(row.label, mode)` then translate |
| Admin-edited dropdown option label | `tDynamicOption(field, optionValue, locale, fallback)` | Read `meta.options[].label` directly |
| Admin-edited boolean-child label | `tDynamicBooleanChild(field, branch, idx, locale, fallback)` | Read `meta.booleanChildren[...]` directly |
| Confirm / cancel / delete / OK button text | Use `confirmDialog` / `alertDialog` defaults (auto-localized) | Render your own Dialog with hardcoded "Cancel" |
| Add an admin editor for `meta.translations` | Drop `<TranslationsEditor>` next to the Label input | Hand-roll a per-locale text input grid |
| Read locale on the server | `await getLocale()` from `@/lib/i18n/server` | Inline cookie / header parsing |
| Read locale on the client | `useLocale()` from `@/lib/i18n` | Inline cookie parsing / `document.cookie` |
| New locale | Add to `SUPPORTED_LOCALES` + new `messages/<locale>.ts` + locale switcher entry | Hardcode `if (locale === "zh-HK")` branches |
| Localized PDF / email / WhatsApp body | DON'T — explicit OUT-of-scope | Pipe `tDynamic` results into anything in `lib/pdf/**` or `lib/email.ts` callers |

## Out-of-scope surfaces (must stay English)

These are deliberately untouched per the i18n plan and the
shared-field-resolver skill:

- Anything inside `lib/pdf/**` — entire tree
- `lib/field-resolver.ts` — used by both dashboard AND PDF; the
  dashboard wraps its output with `tDynamic` at the consumer layer
  instead, so the resolver itself stays locale-blind
- Email subjects / bodies, WhatsApp body templates, share-link
  landing pages
- All currency / date / number formatting
- API contracts, file URLs, document share tokens, audit log
  payloads, user-entered snapshot values

If you need to localize one of these on purpose, it's a scope
change — re-read the plan first.

